. Bender-Baird covers many forms of discrimination that transgender workers face, such as harassment, gender-based dress codes, income-related inequities, bathroom policies, and background checks. Drawing from this analysis, she argues for protections for gender expression in policy decisions, legislative efforts, and for a multipronged approach to workplace discrimination. With its effective balance of personal stories and legal guidance, this book is a much-needed resource for those in the field of gender and employment, from policy analysts to human resource managers to queer studies scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDiscrimination in employment -- United States. 0aDiscrimination in employmentzUnited States. 0aSex discrimination in employment -- Law and legislation -- United States. 0aSex discrimination in employmentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aTransgender people -- Employment -- Law and legislation -- United States. 0aTransgender people -- Employment -- United States. 0aTransgender peoplexEmploymentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aTransgender peoplexEmploymentzUnited States. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aSociology : Sociology of Work. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438436760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438436760/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles